  1. Name the aesthetics, geoms, scales, and facets of the above visualisation. Also name any statistical transformations or special coordinate systems.

Lets break down the following expression which is a combination of the two chunks above:

ggplot(Hitters, aes(x = Hits, y = HmRun)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Hits", y = "Home runs")+ 
  geom_density_2d() +
  labs(title = "Cool density and scatter plot of baseball data") +
  theme_minimal()

The function ggplot() initializes a new ggplot by creating a new ggplot object. Within this function, the arguments are data and mapping. For the data argument, we specify Hitters, which is a baseball dataset from the ISLR package. More information about the dataset can be found by running ?ISLR::Hitters. The mapping argument specifies the aesthetic mapping to use for the plot. Here we set to to aes() which constructs aesthetic mappings. Aesthetic mappings describe how variables in the data are mapped to visual properties (aesthetics) of geoms.

The following layer is the geom layer which takes the data with its aesthetic mapping and combines them to a geom (geometric) object. In our case, we specify this layer using geom_point() which will plot all the observations as points on in the x-y coordinate system.

The next layer assigns the labels to the x and y axes using labs().

The subsequent layer uses geom_density_2d() which calculates and plots the contours of a 2D density estimate. This is a tranformation of the original data which is useful to see how the points are spatially distributed.

Then we call labs() again, but this time was pass the title argument which gives our plot a title.

Finally, we use theme_minimal() to remove the default gray background.

  1. Run the code below to generate data. There will be three vectors in your environment. Put them in a data frame for entering it in a ggplot() call using either the data.frame() or the tibble() function. Give informative names and make sure the types are correct (use the as.<type>() functions). Name the result gg_students.
set.seed(1234)
student_grade  <- rnorm(32, 7)
student_number <- round(runif(32) * 2e6 + 5e6)
programme      <- sample(c("Science", "Social Science"), 32, replace = TRUE)
gg_students <- data.frame("grade" = student_grade, "number" = as.character(student_number), program = as.factor(programme))
  1. Plot the first homeruns_plot again, but map the Hits to the y-axis and the HmRun to the x-axis instead

  geom_point()+

  1. Recreate the same plot once more, but now also map the variable League to the colour aesthetic and the variable Salary to the size aesthetic.

  geom_point()+

  2. Use geom_histogram() to create a histogram of the grades of the students in the gg_students dataset. Play around with the binwidth argument of the geom_histogram() function.

  1. Use geom_density() to create a density plot of the grades of the students in the gg_students dataset. Add the argument fill = "light seagreen" to geom_density().
ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = grade))+
  geom_density(fill = "light seagreen")

  1. Add rug marks to the density plot through geom_rug(). You can edit the colour and size of the rug marks using those arguments within the geom_rug() function.
ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = grade))+
  geom_density(fill = "light seagreen")+
  geom_rug(color = 'red', size = 2)

  1. Increase the data to ink ratio by removing the y axis label, setting the theme to theme_minimal(), and removing the border of the density polygon. Also set the limits of the x-axis to go from 0 to 10 using the xlim() function, because those are the plausible values for a student grade.
ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = grade))+
  geom_density(fill = "light seagreen")+
  geom_rug(color = 'red', size = 2)+
  labs(y = "") +
  xlim(0, 10)+
  theme_minimal()

  1. Create a boxplot of student grades per programme in the gg_students dataset you made earlier: map the programme variable to the x position and the grade to the y position. For extra visual aid, you can additionally map the programme variable to the fill aesthetic.
ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = program, y = grade, fill = program))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  theme_minimal()

  1. What do each of the horizontal lines in the boxplot mean? What do the vertical lines (whiskers) mean?

The horizontal lines in the center of the box indicate the median, and the borders of each box indicate the interquantile range (IQR). The vertical lines are called whiskers and the upper and lower whiskers represent scores outside the middle 50%.

  1. Comparison of distributions across categories can also be done by adding a fill aesthetic to the density plot you made earlier. Try this out. To take care of the overlap, you might want to add some transparency in the geom_density() function using the alpha argument.
ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = grade, fill = program))+
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5)+
  geom_rug(color = 'red', size = 2)+
  labs(y = "")+
  xlim(0, 10)+
  theme_minimal()

  1. Use geom_line() to make a line plot out of the first 200 observations of the variable Volume (the number of trades made on each day) of the Smarket dataset. You will need to create a Day variable using mutate() to map to the x-position. This variable can simply be the integers from 1 to 200. Remember, you can select the first 200 rows using Smarket[1:200, ].
Smarket <- Smarket[1:200,] %>% mutate(Day = 1:200 )
ggplot(Smarket, aes(x = Day, y = Volume))+
  geom_line()+
  theme_minimal()

  1. Give the line a nice colour and increase its size. Also add points of the same colour on top.
ggplot(Smarket, aes(x = Day, y = Volume))+
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1)+
  geom_point(colour = "blue", size = 1)+
  theme_minimal()

  1. Use geom_label(aes(x = your_x, y = your_y, label = "Peak volume")) to add a label to this day. You can use either the values or call the functions. Place the label near the peak!
ggplot(Smarket, aes(x = Day, y = Volume))+
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1)+
  geom_label(aes(x = 170, y = 2.5, label = "Peak volume"))+
  theme_minimal()

  1. Create a data frame called baseball based on the Hitters dataset. In this data frame, create a factor variable which splits players salary range into 3 categories. Tip: use the filter() function to remove the missing values, and then use the cut() function and assign nice labels to the categories. In addition, create a variable which indicates the proportion of career hits that was a home run.
newhitters <- Hitters %>% 
  filter(!is.na(Salary)) %>% 
  mutate(SalaryCat = cut(Salary, breaks = 3, 
         labels = c("Low salary", "Medium salary", "High salary")),
         Proportion_Hits_HomeRun = CHmRun/CHits)
  1. Create a scatter plot where you map CWalks to the x position and the proportion you calculated in the previous exercise to the y position. Fix the y axis limits to (0, 0.4) and the x axis to (0, 1600) using ylim() and xlim(). Add nice x and y axis titles using the labs() function. Save the plot as the variable baseball_plot.
baseball_plot <- 
  ggplot(newhitters, aes(x = CWalks, y = Proportion_Hits_HomeRun))+
  geom_point()+
  ylim(0, 0.4)+
  xlim(0, 1600)+
  labs(x = "Number of walks during player's career", y = "Proportion of home runs")+
  theme_minimal()
  

baseball_plot

  1. Split up this plot into three parts based on the salary range variable you calculated. Use the facet_wrap() function for this; look at the examples in the help file for tips.
baseball_plot + facet_wrap(vars(SalaryCat))

  1. Create an interesting data visualisation based on the Carseats data from the ISLR package.
carseats <- Carseats %>% 
  mutate(PriceDiff = CompPrice - Price) %>% 
  mutate(IncomeCat = cut(Income, breaks = 3, 
         labels = c("Low income", "Medium income", "High income"))) %>% 
  mutate(Advertising = cut(Advertising, breaks = 3, 
         labels = c("Low advertising", "Medium advertising", "High advertising")))

I compute the price difference between the competitor and our location. Higher difference values indicate that our location is cheaper than the competitors. Next, I split Income and Advertising into three categories.

ggplot(carseats, aes(x = PriceDiff, y = Sales, color = Advertising))+
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(vars(IncomeCat))+
  labs(x = "Price Difference with Competitors",
       y = "Sales", 
       title = "Child Car Seat Sales by Income and Advertising Level")
